  {"q": "What is mass spectrometry?", "a": "Mass spectrometry is an analytical technique used to determine the mass and relative abundance of isotopes in a sample."},
  {"q": "What are the main steps in mass spectrometry?", "a": "The main steps in mass spectrometry are ionization, acceleration, deflection, and detection."},
  {"q": "What is ionization in mass spectrometry?", "a": "Ionization is the process where atoms are converted to positive ions by removing electrons."},
  {"q": "Why are ions accelerated in mass spectrometry?", "a": "Ions are accelerated to give them kinetic energy to move through the magnetic field for separation."},
  {"q": "What happens during deflection in mass spectrometry?", "a": "During deflection, ions are bent by a magnetic field based on their mass-to-charge ratio (m/z)."},
  {"q": "What does the detector do in mass spectrometry?", "a": "The detector records the number of ions and their mass-to-charge ratios, producing a mass spectrum."},
  {"q": "What is the formula for relative atomic mass using mass spectrometry?", "a": "Relative atomic mass = (Σ (isotope mass × relative abundance)) / 100."},
  {"q": "Why must atoms be ionized in mass spectrometry?", "a": "Atoms must be ionized so they can be accelerated and deflected in the electric and magnetic fields."},
  {"q": "What is a mass spectrum?", "a": "A mass spectrum is a graph showing the relative abundance of detected ions versus their mass-to-charge ratios."},
  {"q": "What does m/z stand for?", "a": "m/z stands for mass-to-charge ratio, used to identify ions in mass spectrometry."},

